title Grain lineage cloned whole to gratitude, siloed to plain module-named use
prompt Kaeden asked to apply the silo technique to six documents (two Codeberg torus/toroidal whitepapers and four local Downloads: topos-aether-agni, two Silken Ground editions, the Grain Point) — cloning each whole into gratitude, then writing siloed versions that adapt them into secular, Urbit-Galaxy-PR-CONTRIBUTING-compatible, High-Output-Management-clear English with common words and this fork's own module names, documenting the siloed set and citing the siloed versions in any Acme-facing writing. Kaeden moved me to Fable 5 1M Max for this.
think Read all six sources first — the four local files directly and the two Codeberg whitepapers via their raw URLs (verified the fetched markdown began with clean frontmatter, not HTML chrome) — before deciding structure. Studied the existing astrology silo and IronBeetle silo to match this fork's own established silo discipline (own-voice understanding, source held whole, never quoted) rather than inventing a new pattern.
think Cloned all six whole into gratitude/grain-lineage/ with a README naming each source and its authors, and confirmed the new subfolder is git-trackable (not caught by the gratitude re-ignore globs that only cover fetched dependency dirs like nix/ and s6/).
think Recognized the real work of siloing here as separation, not summary: each source wraps genuine engineering (toroidal geometry's uniform-topology and bounded-distance properties; natural-gradient descent on compact manifolds; the pure-transition-function static-allocation kernel; one-carrier-many-flows convergence; the dual-description design principle; the sheaf-gluing value model) inside a visionary, devotional, and contested-physics register. The silo keeps the checkable engineering and plainly labels the aether/Vedic/Gospel register as framing to set aside, so a skeptical PR reviewer can weigh the strong parts without the contested parts dragging on them.
think Built a translation table so no reader learns two naming systems at once: Grain OS to Rye OS, Grain Style to TAME Guidance, Arvo to the Glow kernel variants, Hoon to Glow, the Loom to Tally, the grain point to Mantra's fold head, sheaf/topos to Bron+Mantra, Langlands/mirror-symmetry to the dual-description principle, aether claims labeled as contested and separated from the geometry.
think Ended each silo with an honest "what this actually gives this fork" tied to a specific real surface (Comlink/Caravan ring topology, the Nock interpreter and Lantern sampling as bounded-optimization targets, the four Glow kernel variants as transition functions over one log, Linengrow's transparent-ledger civic thesis, Bron/Mantra as sheaf-gluing, a dual-description witness pattern) — so the silo produces citable understanding, not adopted decisions.
obs The Grain Point silo is the most immediately load-bearing of the six: it restates this fork's own already-stated spine (state as a pure fold over an append-only signed-fact log) in a form that directly justifies why the four Glow kernel variants can share one design, and bridges Arvo's proven kernel shape to this fork's Mantra+Caravan+Tally seam. Flagged it as the document most likely to inform a future real Glow-kernel proposal.
obs Committed in two atomic parts on purpose — held-whole originals first, siloed adaptations second — so the gratitude "held whole, never edited" boundary and the "adaptation lives elsewhere" boundary are visible in the history itself, not just asserted in prose.
file gratitude/grain-lineage/ why: six source documents held whole and unaltered, with an index README and authorship/source lines
file gratitude/README.md why: one discoverable index entry pointing at both the whole copies and the silo
file external-research/grain-lineage-silo/ why: the six secular, module-named siloed adaptations plus an index README with the translation table and the how-it-informs-designs note
recommend keep-going — this was additive silo work following an established pattern; no rename, no code, no design fork opened. The one item worth Kaeden's eventual word is whether the Grain Point silo should graduate into a real Glow-kernel design proposal, which would be its own properly-sized future pass.
